e? This book explores Martin's and HBO's approaches to and beliefs about the Middle Ages and how those beliefs fall into traditional medievalist and fantastic literary patterns. Examining both books and programme from a range of critical approaches - medievalism theory, gender theory, queer theory, postcolonial theory, andrace theory - Dr Carroll analyzes how the drive for historical realism affects the books' and show's treatment of men, women, people of colour, sexuality, and imperialism, as well as how the author and showrunners discuss these effects outside the texts themselves. SHILOH CARROLL teaches in the writing center at Tennessee State University.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMedievalism in literature. 0aMedievalism on television. 4aFilm & Theatre. 4aMedieval History. 4aMedieval Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Medieval.2bisacsh  aA Song of Ice and Fire.  aGame of Thrones.  aGeorge R.R. Martin.  aMedievalism.  aMiddle Ages.  aauthentic medieval.  acultural narratives.  afantasy literature.  afantasy world.  agender theory.  ahistorical authenticity.  ahistorical realism.  aliterary analysis.  amedieval fantasy.  amedieval literature.  apostcolonial theory.  arace theory.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311143106240uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781787441941?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781787441941423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781787441941/original  a978-3-11-143106-2  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles